are currently facing complex issues, dealing for example with increased competition, organising (logistic) processes, acquiring and using information technology, attracting the necessary financial resources and recruiting good, skilled staff. Managers are not only expected to have knowledge and expertise in the field of economics, but also in such areas as psychology, politics, sociology and law. In making decisions, they need to be able to see the cohesion between these disciplines and be aware of how they affect each other.]]></td></t><t><tid>135</tid><td xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[It focuses on the (dis)functioning of markets and the relationship between the market and government. Topics include the development of employment or the impact of public expenditure on investments of companies. ]]></td></t><t><tid>136</tid><td xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Subjects include monetary economics, banking, investments and portfolio theory and advanced corporate finance. Financial aspects are emphasised in all these areas. The main topics are the operation of international financial markets, government intervention, and financing and investment decisions in the business and banking sectors in the context of the international financial environment.]]></td></t><t><tid>137</tid><td xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Honours students work together with the best students of other programmes and they motivate each other to get the most out of their studies. If your grade is at least a seven and a half (1-10 scale) for your regular courses, and you complete an honours programme of at least 30 credits you will obtain an honours diploma in addition to your Bachelor's diploma. The honours programme provides the unique chance for broader self-development and to take an interest in scientific, societal, cultural, philosophical and current themes.]]></td></t><orgUnitLocationId><![CDATA[Amsterdam]]></orgUnitLocationId><facultyId><![CDATA[eb]]></facultyId><targetMarket>nl</targetMarket><targetMarket>int</targetM